[stdout] {"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772606590460,"sessionID":"ses_3486a21eeffezuyMBWClEkj654","part":{"id":"prt_cb7960cda001tg7Ytb4sJrnhJa","sessionID":"ses_3486a21eeffezuyMBWClEkj654","messageID":"msg_cb795ffe4001eJao8i9YvXj52B","type":"tool","callID":"call_0bNWJlo5FdutiJdoiRI8bPlp","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/CLI.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/CLI.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # tsci CLI primer\n2: \n3: Prereqs\n4: - Node.js or Bun\n5: - Install the tscircuit CLI (global install):\n6:   - npm: `npm install -g tscircuit`\n7:   - bun: `bun install --global tscircuit`\n8: \n9: Core commands\n10: \n11: 1) Create / bootstrap a project\n12: - `tsci init` (interactive)\n13: - `tsci init -y` (accept defaults)\n14: \n15: Typical output includes:\n16: - `index.tsx` (main circuit entrypoint)\n17: - `package.json`, `tsconfig.json`\n18: - `tscircuit.config.json`\n19: \n20: 2) Preview locally (interactive)\n21: - `tsci dev`\n22: - Opens a local preview server (commonly https://localhost:3020)\n23: - Note: For AI-driven iteration, prefer `tsci build` over `tsci dev`—dev mode is primarily for interactive visual feedback.\n24: \n25: 3) Search the ecosystem\n26: - `tsci search \"<query>\"`\n27:   - Finds footprints, components, and packages across multiple sources\n28: \n29: Search flags:\n30: - `--jlcpcb` (or `--lcsc`) – Search JLCPCB/LCSC components by name or part number\n31: - `--kicad` – Search KiCad footprint library\n32: - `--tscircuit` – Search tscircuit registry packages\n33: \n34: Examples:\n35: ```bash\n36: # Search JLCPCB for microcontrollers\n37: tsci search --jlcpcb \"ATmega328\"\n38: # Output: ATMEGA328P-AU (C14877) - stock: 20,226\n39: \n40: # Search JLCPCB by part number\n41: tsci search --jlcpcb \"C14877\"\n42: \n43: # Search for USB-C connectors on JLCPCB\n44: tsci search --jlcpcb \"USB-C 16pin\"\n45: \n46: # Search KiCad footprints\n47: tsci search --kicad \"QFP-32\"\n48: # Output: kicad:Package_QFP/LQFP-32_5x5mm_P0.5mm\n49: \n50: # Search KiCad for SMD resistor footprints\n51: tsci search --kicad \"0402\"\n52: \n53: # Search tscircuit registry for existing projects\n54: tsci search --tscircuit \"LED\"\n55: # Output: seveibar/usb-c-flashlight - Stars: 5\n56: \n57: # Search without flags (searches all sources)\n58: tsci search \"ESP32\"\n59: ```\n60: \n61: 4) Add existing registry packages to your project\n62: - `tsci add <author/pkg>`\n63:   - Use when a reusable tscircuit package already exists in the registry\n64:   - Example: `tsci add seveibar/PICO_W`\n65:   - Imports look like: `import { PICO_W } from \"@tsci/seveibar.PICO_W\"`\n66:   - The `@tsci/` scope with dot notation (`author.pkg`) is the registry convention\n67: \n68: 5) Import components (e.g., from JLCPCB)\n69: - `tsci import <query>`\n70:   - Use when you need to bring a specific part into your project\n71:   - Searches both the tscircuit registry and JLCPCB parts database\n72:   - Opens an interactive picker to select and import the component\n73: \n74: Workflow:\n75: ```bash\n76: # First, search to find the part number\n77: tsci search --jlcpcb \"ATmega328\"\n78: # Output: ATMEGA328P-AU (C14877) - stock: 20,226\n79: \n80: # Then import using the part number or name\n81: tsci import \"C14877\"\n82: # or\n83: tsci import \"ATmega328\"\n84: ```\n85: \n86: The interactive picker shows:\n87: - Registry packages (already wrapped by other users): `author/PART_NAME`\n88: - JLCPCB parts (raw import): `[jlcpcb] PART_NAME (CXXXXXX)`\n89: \n90: Tip: If someone has already imported the part, prefer the registry version—it may have better pin mappings or schematic symbols.\n91: \n92: 6) Build (generate circuit.json)\n93: \n94: Before building, it can be a good idea to check placement of the entire board or a specific component with `tsci check placement [file] [refdes]`\n95: \n96: - `tsci build` (auto-detects entrypoint)\n97: - `tsci build path/to/file.circuit.tsx`\n98: \n99: Notes\n100: - If no path is provided, `tsci build` searches for `index.tsx` or `mainEntrypoint` in `tscircuit.config.json`.\n101: - `*.circuit.tsx` files are built automatically.\n102: - Outputs go to `dist/`.\n103: \n104: Useful flags\n105: - `--ignore-errors` (CI/automation)\n106: - `--ignore-warnings`\n107: - `--all-images` (emit PCB/schematic/3D renders into `dist/`)\n108: \n109: DRC (Design Rule Check)\n110: - DRC errors are often reported but can frequently be ignored during development.\n111: - Focus on getting the circuit correct first; DRC violations can be addressed later when preparing for manufacturing.\n112: \n113: 7) Export (SVG/netlist/3D/library)\n114: - `tsci export <file> -f <format>`\n115: \n116: Common formats\n117: - `schematic-svg`\n118: - `pcb-svg`\n119: - `readable-netlist`\n120: - `specctra-dsn`\n121: - `gltf` / `glb`\n122: - `kicad-library`\n123: \n124: 8) Visual snapshots for analysis and verification\n125: - `tsci snapshot` generates visual outputs (schematic/PCB, optionally 3D) and writes/overwrites snapshots by default.\n126: - Use these visuals to inspect placement, orientation, and overall circuit understanding during iteration.\n127: - `tsci snapshot --test` switches to regression-test mode: it fails on visual diffs and does **not** overwrite snapshots.\n128: - `tsci snapshot --pcb-only` generates only PCB visuals, which is especially useful for placement-focused iteration.\n129: - `tsci snapshot --3d` includes 3D snapshots in the output.\n130: \n131: Recommended pattern:\n132: ```bash\n133: # During development: generate fresh visuals for analysis and review\n134: tsci snapshot\n135: \n136: # During placement-heavy iterations: focus only on PCB output\n137: tsci snapshot --pcb-only\n138: \n139: # In CI/regression checks: detect unexpected visual changes without overwriting\n140: tsci snapshot --test\n141: ```\n142: \n143: 9) Auth / publish\n144: - `tsci login` (browser-based)\n145: - `tsci push` (publish package)\n146: - `tsci auth print-token`\n147: \n148: Guidance\n149: - Prefer `tsci --help` and `tsci <cmd> --help` when unsure about flags.\n150: - Avoid `tsci push` unless the user explicitly asks to publish.\n\n(End of file - total 150 lines)\n</content>","title":"workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/CLI.md","metadata":{"preview":"# tsci CLI primer\n\nPrereqs\n- Node.js or Bun\n- Install the tscircuit CLI (global install):\n  - npm: `npm install -g tscircuit`\n  - bun: `bun install --global tscircuit`\n\nCore commands\n\n1) Create / bootstrap a project\n- `tsci init` (interactive)\n- `tsci init -y` (accept defaults)\n\nTypical output includes:\n- `index.tsx` (main circuit entrypoint)\n- `package.json`, `tsconfig.json`\n- `tscircuit.config.json`\n\n2) Preview locally (interactive)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1772606590183,"end":1772606590458}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.summary","summary":"**Assess","format":"openai-responses-v1","index":0},{"type":"reasoning.summary","summary":"ing","format":"openai-responses-v1","index":0},{"type":"reasoning.summary","summary":" J","format":"openai-responses-v1","index":0},{"type":"reasoning.summary","summary":"LC","format":"openai-responses-v1","index":0},{"type":"reasoning.summary","summary":"PCB","format":"openai-responses-v1","index":0},{"type":"reasoning.summary","summary":" import","format":"openai-responses-v1","index":0},{"type":"reasoning.summary","summary":" options","format":"openai-responses-v1","index":0},{"type":"reasoning.summary","summary":"**","format":"openai-responses-v1","index":0},{"type":"reasoning.encrypted","data":"gAAAAABpp9R-FdHbRIVedjoYT1WwGjj2-rQJignl0r5xQ7-p6NrZkys2_LmZv0psvPpd7dEqxgt36cKbSkF8LaQ8dSAwRLoRmKfHidgDSzil1kZQQL6jZ7e7xTFVxR93Zif0pmVHKqkgCVg7HEoui0XcTXPfrm9AWW7xPnrZhcjY-2rIyvAUHvV6GlIW0AqRupLiVVYFkSPzNkyNQ-eZETRj7d3uR5YRtTN-Kq-XwLykuRZ11RWAM1c9-ANbzwEPfxxaASCWMYuKojSuSxNu1xYMRKTMUGKLhgIChWgJJnp8_FooMy6IW434YCUL5PO4rXcK